  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most property transactions in Brisbane involve a buyer paying a cash deposit at the time of exchange, typically 10 per cent of the purchase price, held in the agent's trust account until settlement. But occasionally a buyer will ask to substitute a deposit bond instead of cash. If you are the seller and this request lands on your desk, it is worth understanding exactly what you are agreeing to before you sign off.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a deposit bond is</h2>
      <p>A deposit bond is a financial instrument issued by an insurance company or a bank that stands in for a cash deposit at the time of contract exchange. Instead of the buyer handing over a cheque or transferring funds into trust, they provide a document that guarantees the seller will receive the deposit amount if the buyer fails to complete the purchase. The bond is not cash. The bond issuer has agreed to pay out a specified sum to the seller in the event of buyer default, but that money is only released after a claims process, not immediately.</p>

      <p>The bond does not change the purchase price, the contract terms, or the settlement timeline. From the outside, the contract looks the same. The only difference is that where a cash deposit would sit in trust accruing interest until settlement, a deposit bond sits in the contract as a guarantee. At settlement, the buyer pays the full purchase price, and the bond is cancelled. It is only triggered if the buyer walks away without completing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why buyers use deposit bonds</h2>
      <p>Buyers request deposit bonds for a few common reasons. The most frequent is that their equity or savings are tied up in another property that has not yet settled. A buyer who has exchanged contracts on their current home but not yet completed may have limited liquidity and cannot draw down on that equity until their own settlement clears. Rather than breaking a term deposit or borrowing short-term bridge funds at cost, they obtain a deposit bond to cover the exchange period.</p>

      <p>Buyers purchasing off-the-plan properties with long settlement periods, sometimes twelve to twenty-four months, also commonly use deposit bonds. In those cases, the argument is that it makes little financial sense to park a large cash sum in trust for two years when the money could be working elsewhere. The bond provides the guarantee the developer or vendor needs without locking up the buyer's capital for an extended period.</p>

      <p>Some buyers also hold funds in term deposits or investment accounts where breaking early would trigger fees or forgo returns. For them, the cost of a deposit bond, typically a few hundred dollars paid by the buyer depending on the bond amount and term, is cheaper than breaking their investment early. That cost is borne entirely by the buyer, not you.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">You are not required to accept one</h2>
      <p>This is the most important thing to understand: as a seller in Queensland, you are not legally obligated to accept a deposit bond. The standard REIQ contract of sale specifies that the deposit is to be paid in cash unless the seller expressly agrees otherwise. If you receive an offer accompanied by a deposit bond and you do not want to accept it, you can decline and require the deposit to be paid in cash as a condition of proceeding.</p>

      <p>Some sellers assume they have to accept whatever the buyer offers, or that declining a deposit bond will kill the deal. Neither is necessarily true. Many buyers who request deposit bonds can access cash if the seller requires it, particularly if the gap to exchange is short. If the buyer cannot produce cash at all under any circumstances, that information itself is worth knowing before you exchange.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The risk difference between cash and a bond</h2>
      <p>With a cash deposit, if the buyer defaults, you keep the deposit immediately. The funds are already held in trust. Your solicitor applies to release them to you and, subject to any dispute resolution, you have the money. The process is relatively clean and typically resolves without extended legal proceedings.</p>

      <p>With a deposit bond, if the buyer defaults, you must lodge a claim with the bond issuer. The issuer will investigate the claim, verify that default has occurred in accordance with the contract terms, and assess whether the payout is warranted. This takes time. In contested matters, it can involve legal correspondence or action between your solicitor, the buyer's solicitor, and the bond issuer. You will ultimately receive the money if the default is genuine and the bond is valid, but the path there is longer and can involve legal costs that would not have arisen with a cash deposit.</p>

      <p>For a transaction that proceeds to settlement without incident, the distinction is irrelevant. The bond is cancelled, the buyer pays the full price, and you receive your proceeds at settlement. The risk only materialises if the buyer defaults, which in most well-qualified purchases does not happen. But the seller takes on that additional process risk in exchange for accommodating the buyer's liquidity preference. Whether that is an acceptable tradeoff is a judgement call, and it depends on the buyer's profile and financial position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to be cautious</h2>
      <p>A buyer who cannot produce a cash deposit warrants a closer look. The inability to access ten per cent of the purchase price in liquid form can, in some cases, indicate a stretched financial position. It does not automatically mean the buyer cannot complete: there are perfectly creditworthy buyers who are asset-rich and cash-poor at the moment of exchange. But it is a reason to ask questions rather than simply agree.</p>

      <p>Before accepting a deposit bond, your solicitor and your agent should establish clearly why the buyer cannot pay cash, whether their finance is fully approved and unconditional or still subject to conditions, and what the buyer's settlement plan looks like. If the buyer's finance is still in assessment, the situation warrants particular caution. A deposit bond does not protect you from a buyer whose finance falls through mid-campaign in a way that leaves the contract in dispute.</p>

      <p>Deposit bonds are most commonly and reasonably accepted in two circumstances: off-the-plan or new development purchases where long settlement periods make cash holding impractical, and high-value property transactions where the deposit sum is large and the buyer's liquidity situation is well understood and legitimate. They are less commonly accepted in standard residential resale transactions between private buyers and sellers, particularly where the settlement period is short and cash should be accessible.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do before agreeing</h2>
      <p>If your buyer has requested a deposit bond and you are inclined to consider it, the practical steps are straightforward. Ask your solicitor to review the bond document before you sign any variation to the contract. A valid deposit bond will name the seller as beneficiary, specify the bond amount, the issuing institution, and the expiry date, and confirm that the bond covers the full deposit amount required under the contract. Your solicitor will identify any gaps or concerns.</p>

      <p>Also check that the bond's expiry date extends at least to your settlement date, with some buffer. A bond that expires before settlement provides no protection during the settlement period itself. Bond terms should be confirmed and any required extension arranged before exchange, not after.</p>

      <p>The bottom line is that accepting a deposit bond is a commercial decision that changes your risk profile in a specific way. For well-qualified buyers with a legitimate and clear reason for requesting the bond, it is often a reasonable accommodation. For buyers whose financial position is unclear or whose reason for avoiding a cash deposit does not stack up, it is a reason to pause before proceeding. Your solicitor is the right person to advise you, and you should not feel pressured to agree simply because the buyer has asked.</p>

